rComments: He looks like a zombie, but he is warm in heart. Nothing unusual excepts for his walking style.

Professor Green is the BEST professor I've had at U of T. He is exceptionally smart and talented at explaining the material, which is particularly well organized and to the point. He captivates attention easily and makes lectures especially interesting. He cares deeply about his students and is very FAIR in everything he does. Simply the BEST!

PSA, all his readings can be found in course reverse as PDFs, no need to buy the course book. Take good notes during lecture and describe your notes on the in class tests. I expect it would be hard to get an A in this class but easy to get a solid B without really trying.

His lectures were pretty short but he provided a lot of supplementary information to the readings that I found helpful. We didn't use any lecture slides; he would read from his notes (which was fine with me). He wasn't very accessible, though.

He uses a very traditional way of teaching that he used no slide but the blackboard. He was helpful when students asked about the tests and the course consists of two open book essay tests and a "bring home test". It's important to do the readings and write down all the quotes that he mentioned in class in the test to get good grades.

He respects his students since he always trying to remember each student's name which is kind of sweet. However, his voice is really deep so sometimes I am not sure what word he just said. He is basically reading from his notes, so to get good grades, all you need to do is to write down every sentence he said and write them on your test paper.

While he is a nice dude, I find he is disrespectful to his student's time. He is always late for lecture. Also, he doesn't add any extra insight to the material. He just summarizes the readings. You definitely do not need to go to class if you do the readings. He also took up to a week to get back to my email on multiple occasions. 3 exams only.
3 him! He is so sweet and genuine! Amazing Professor!

One of the best professors I've had at uoft thus far. He's incredibly coherent and to the point. Tests are heavily weighted, but marked fairly. Very approachable. I found the videos refreshing. And his tests are open book. I'd definitely take another class with him!
Hottest professor alert.

Professor Green is one of the best professors I have ever had. I took SOC365H1 with him last semester and loved it. However, I must warn you all about heavily weighted midterms and exams, which can be a game changer. Marking was fair and tests were reasonable as well. If you put in the work, you will do more than fine.

Best professor I've had at UofT. So good at explaining the material and his lecture style is simplistic yet so helpful and intriguing. He has a way to captivate attention and make things interesting. Such a nice guy also. Wants to get to know his students. Incredible experience with prof. Green!

Great prof. His lectures are well paced and clear.  Though he likes to show a lot of youtube videos in class that you can watch at home. Annoying when you're forced to sit through them in lame con hall.  Definitely a nice change from Brym's lectures.

Definitely one the most approachable professor in the soc department. I never had a class with him in first year, but take his class in my final year in a smaller class setting definitely showed that he's a prof who genuinely cares about his students. He provides excellent feedback on assignments. It's a different experience, take his class!
He explains material so so well! He made the course content so much easier with his humour and clarity. Its the kind of lectures I will always expect to have in big university like UofT.
Great professor, he is very engaging and uses modern context to bring light to sociological topics. Provides a good breather from Profsssor Brym's lectures.
Really interesting lectures!
Great professor, clearly enthusiastic about the content, organized and a fantastic and engaging professor.  Maintains a great rhythm to his lectures.  Be careful on the multiple choice test.

Good personality, engaging lectures and material. The course doesn't have much material to begin with so his teaching is pretty good in consideration to that. Easy tests, easy marking, easy assignments. I had no experience asking him for help and such, cause the material was simple. Posts lectures on time. Overall 7.7/10 Good.

Laziest professor going. I've never watched so much YouTube, and the last class, which should have been exam review, was an hour and a half of movie watching that wasn't even on the final. Frequently contradicts the text and then would ask on tests for the answer 'he gave' in class, even if the textbook said something different. Tests = obscure.

He's an awful teacher. Reads off his notes the entire time. Yeah, he shows a lot of YouTube videos, but I can look at that stuff on my own time. Going to his classes was an absolute waste that I started skipping frequently. All you have to do is read the lecture slides and the text book. He made me drop my sociology course next semester.

My favorite lecture this semester. He definitely did a good job of making the 2 hour class enjoyable. Only thing  I had a problem with was he didn't really give much detail about what to expect on his exams. Other then that great teacher
awesome.. but doesn't help explain the books at all. theres far too much useless info in the books which he makes us read.
Very funny. Love his jokes. Makes the topic very enjoyable. Love the Youtube videos! Wished he taught the entire course instead of just one semester.
he was a funny guy, I liked his style of teaching, it allowed us to formulate opinions and come to conclusions on our own, instead of picking them right out of a textbook.

Hilarious, makes you want to go to class and pay attention. Good powerpoint slide and uses youtube clips to explain things, also funny personal anecdotes. An amazing prof, make sure you go to class though because the majority of what he tests on is what he says in lecture.
Loved going to lectures, and really enjoyed his humour/ the youtube clips.
with great sense of humour and his lectures are really funny and entertaining. the examples and cases used in lectures are interesting and related, i enjoyed his lecutres very much.
Sociology is not the same without him teaching it. I wish he taught more lectures to our class for this semester. he was the best! :D
Really nice and helpful. Just make sure you attend classes because the majority of his test is based on what he says in his lectures.

I always looked forward to my sociology lecture; Prof. Green keeps his presentations extremely interesting and very well organized, and makes it easy to follow along and pay attention. His personal stories and sense of humor also enrich the class. Because of this class, I'm going to major or minor in sociology now. Thank you Professor Green!

A really great professor overall. He makes lots of jokes, he keeps my attention, and did I mention the fact that he's really buff? The exams are harder than you'd expect from his easy going personality. Make sure you to really study the lecture notes when you study for the exams, the textbook material isnt as prevalent in the exams

Really nice guy... first half consisted of him lecturing and second half was student presentations. Marked fairly and entertained with his sense of humour. Obviously well-liked by his students and for good reason.
Great lecturer, great course, valuable learning experience

This was Green's 1st time teaching this course & he repeated some films & material covered in UNI255H. Result: easy & frustrating, for me at least. His lectures were enjoyable, but his analysis was limited. He left most of the challenging of theories to students & often seemed surprized when asked a controdictory question. Heavy on G, light on LBTQ
If you do the reading and pay attention you'll get a lot out of this class.  Green gives thorough lectures on materials and is entertaining but challenging.   Grading is hard though.

Great course.  Professor Green really knows his stuff.  I am a sociology major, and his lectures focus not only on gender, but on linking gender to the discipline as a whole.  I have really learned a lot from this class.  But be warned: don't take Green's easy going manner for a push-over prof!  He demands a lot on his exams, so pay attention!
Dr. Green's class is one of the best courses i have taken while at UofT.  The class is definately challenging but Green makes it so interesting -
WOW!  Professor Green is amazing!  One of the best professors I have encountered at university.
Professor is terrific.  Lectures are carefully presented, the course material is varied and interesting, discussion is encouraged and he clearly cares about learning.  I highly recommend!
No Comments
